'''Allegheny Airlines Flight 736''' was a regularly scheduled flight that crashed while attempting to land at [[Bradford Regional Airport]] in [[Bradford, Pennsylvania]] on December 24, 1968. Twenty of the 47 occupants on board were killed.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|1}}

==Aircraft==
Flight 736 was operated using a [[Convair CV-580]] (registration number ''N5802''). The aircraft was originally certificated as a [[Convair CV-240 family|Convair CV-440]] on March 4, 1957, but was modified to include upgraded turbine engines and propellers and re-certificated as a CV-580 on May 25, 1965. At the time of the accident, the aircraft had accumulated a total of 29,173 flight hours.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|(Appendix C)}}

==Flight==
Flight 736 took off from [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]] bound for [[Washington D.C.]], with intermediate stops in [[Erie, Pennsylvania|Erie]], Bradford, and [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]].<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|2}} The flight was uneventful until the aircraft began its approach to Bradford.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|2}}

At 19:57 [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Standard Time]], Flight 736 reported passing a [[Distance measuring equipment|DME]] east of Erie, and was instructed to descend to 4,000 feet and cleared for an approach to Bradford.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|2}} At the same time, Flight 736 was advised that, at the last hourly observation, Bradford weather reported light snow showers, blowing snow, and one mile visibility.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|2}} At 20:05, [[air traffic control|Bradford approach controllers]] advised Flight 736 again of light snow, blowing snow, and one mile visibility. Flight 736 acknowledged each weather advisory.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|2}} At 20:08, Flight 736 reported that they were turning inbound for runway 32 and they were informed the wind was 290&nbsp;degrees at 15&nbsp;knots.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|3}} This was Flight 736's last transmission before the crash.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|3}}

Flight 736 continued to descend until the aircraft first struck trees approximately 2-1/8 nautical miles short of the runway. The airplane cut through the trees for a further 800&nbsp;feet, extensively damaging the engines, until it impacted the ground.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|10}} The fuselage came to rest inverted with the top portion (roof) of the fuselage torn away.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|12}} Most of the survivors were seated toward the back of the aircraft and were wearing seatbelts, remaining in their seats until the plane came to a halt.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|12}} Passengers who were able to free themselves then worked to free the remaining survivors.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|12–13}} Due to a blinding snowstorm, rescue workers were initially prevented from reaching the crash site.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7g8zAAAAIBAJ&sjid=pgEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2636,3983491&dq=allegheny+airlines+bradford&hl=en Airliner down in Pennsylvania]</ref> Survivors started a bonfire outside of the aircraft using wood, seat cushions, and luggage to keep warm and attract rescuers to the crash site.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|13}}<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=KqFhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LrwMAAAAIBAJ&pg=7211,6492420&dq=allegheny+airlines+bradford&hl=en 19 are killed in Christmas Eve plane crash; 27 survive]</ref>

==Investigation==
The [[National Transportation Safety Board]] investigated the accident.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|1}}  After reviewing the [[cockpit voice recorder]] and [[flight data recorder]], the NTSB determined that the flight was flawless until the flight reached a DME 2.9 miles from the airport.  The minimum altitude at the 2.9 mile DME was 2,900 feet above mean sea level; after reaching the DME, Flight 736 was authorized only to descend to the minimum descent altitude (MDA) of 2,543 feet.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|7}}  However, the aircraft continued to descend below the MDA until it contacted the trees at an altitude 462 feet below the MDA.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|22}}  The NTSB concluded that neither pilot was aware of the aircraft's proximity to the ground until initial contact with trees, at which point the first officer yelled, "Pull up."<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|18}}  The pilots then attempted to pull up, but one second later the right wing struck a large tree, causing the aircraft to roll over.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|18}}

The investigators focused on determining why the pilots allowed the aircraft to descend below the MDA.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|18}} Crew fatigue, instrument or autopilot malfunction, and other mechanical issues were all considered and dismissed as unlikely causes.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|18–23}} The NTSB concluded that the most likely explanation was that the descent was unintentional and resulted from both pilots looking away from the instruments, having instead focused on making visual contact with the runway.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|23}} Based on cockpit conversations and weather data, the NTSB also concluded that while light snow and 1-mile visibility was reported to the pilots from the Bradford airport, weather conditions and visibility may have been substantially worse in the final approach area.<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|28}}

The NTSB determined the probable cause to be "the continuation of the descent from the final approach fix through the Minimum Descent Altitude and into obstructing terrain at a time when both flight crewmembers were looking outside the aircraft in an attempt to establish visual reference to the ground. Contributing factors were the minimal visual references available at night on the approaches to the Bradford Regional Airport; a small but critical navigational error during the later stages of the approach; and a rapid change in visibility conditions that was not known to the crew."<ref name="AAR-70-04" />{{rp|28}}

==Aftermath==
Less than two weeks after Flight 736 crashed, [[Allegheny Airlines Flight 737]] also went down on approach to Bradford Airport. Both aircraft were approaching the same runway but in opposite directions at the time of the crashes.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Q24eAAAAIBAJ&sjid=l8kEAAAAIBAJ&pg=895,1744100&dq=allegheny+airlines+bradford&hl=en Common factor in crashes sought]</ref> Shortly after Flight 737's crash, Allegheny Airlines self-imposed new rules for landings at airports. The rules required visibility of 1,000&nbsp;feet up and three miles out for any airport without instrument landing systems.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=iackAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3GwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7235,2383458&dq=allegheny+airlines+bradford&hl=en Allegheny's restrictions cut landings]</ref>

Almost 42&nbsp;years after the crash, one of its survivors announced she was paying for a plaque for the flight's victims, survivors, and rescuers.<ref>[http://old.post-gazette.com/pg/10113/1052764-100.stm Memorial planned for 1968 Bradford plane crash]</ref>

