{{Infobox storm | name = Grand Harbour tornado | image = Siegemaltakl1.jpg | alt = | caption = The Grand Harbour as it looked in [[Great Siege of Malta|the siege of 1565]]. | formed = September 23, 1551 or 1556 | active = | dissipated = | lowest pressure = | lowest temperature = | tornadoes = | fujitascale = | tornado duration = | highest winds = | gusts = | maximum snow = | power outages = | total fatalities = 600 fatalities (estimated) | damages = | affected = [[Grand Harbour]], Malta | location = | current advisories = | enhanced = | notes = }}
The '''Grand Harbour of Malta tornado''' was a [[tornado]] that hit the [[Grand Harbour]] of [[Malta]] on September 23, 1551 or 1556 (sources conflict) with very intense strength. It began as a [[waterspout]] killing at least 600&nbsp;people, making it one of the deadliest & most destructive tornado in world history until it surpassed by a tornado in 1989..<ref>{{cite web|title=British & European Tornado Extremes|url=http://www.torro.org.uk/site/whirlwind_info.php|publisher=The Tornado and storm Research Organisation|accessdate=28 July 2011}}</ref> At least four of [[Navy of the Order of Saint John|the Order's galleys]], named ''Santa Fè'', ''San Michele'', ''San Filippo'' and ''San Claudio'', capsized in the tornado.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Abela|first1=Joe|title=Claude de la Sengle (1494 - 1557)|url=http://www.islalocalcouncil.com/promseng.htm#claude|publisher=Senglea Local Council|accessdate=5 October 2014}}</ref>
