[[image:HELWIN BETA (14530296941).jpg|thumb|right|The HelWin Beta platform topside.]] '''HVDC HelWin2''' is a [[high voltage direct current]] (HVDC) link built to transmit [[offshore wind power]] to the [[power grid]] of the [[Germany|German mainland]]. The project differs from most HVDC systems in that one of the two [[HVDC converter station|converter stations]] is built on a platform in the sea. [[HVDC converter#Voltage-Sourced Converter|Voltage-Sourced Converters]] with DC ratings of 690&nbsp;MW, ±320&nbsp;kV are used and the total cable length is 130&nbsp;km. The project was built by the [[Siemens]]/[[Prysmian Group|Prysmian]] consortium with the offshore platform built by [[Heerema Marine Contractors|Heerema]]<ref>[http://hfg.heerema.com/content/news-media/news-releases/news-detail/article/helwin2-offshore-hvdc-platform/ HelWin2 Offshore HVDC platform], [[Heerema Marine Contractors|Heerema]] press release, 13 June 2012.</ref><ref>[http://hfg.heerema.com/content/news-media/news-releases/news-detail/article/start-construction-tennets-helwin-beta-platform/ Start construction TenneT's HelWin beta platform], [[Heerema Marine Contractors|Heerema]] press release, 19 Oct 2012.</ref> in [[Zwijndrecht, Netherlands]]. The topside measures 98 m x 42 m x 28 m and weighs 10200 tonnes. The project was handed over to its owner, [[TenneT]], in June 2015, the fourth such project to be completed in 2015.<ref>[http://www.offshorewind.biz/2015/06/22/tennet-takes-over-helwin2/?uid=51177 TenneT Takes Over HelWin2], OffshoreWind.biz, 22 June 2015. </ref>
