'''SgurrEnergy''' is an [[engineering]] consultancy specialising in [[renewable energy]] projects.  The company is based in [[Glasgow]], Scotland, and has offices in [[Beijing]], China; [[Pune]], India; [[Paris]], France; [[Wexford]], Ireland; [[Portland, Maine|Portland]], Maine; [[Vancouver]], British Columbia; and [[Mexico City]], Mexico as of January 2016.

SgurrEnergy was established in 2002 by company directors Ian Irvine and Steve McDonald. The company specialises in [[wind farms]], [[Marine (ocean)|marine]] farms, [[bioenergy]] systems, [[hydroelectricity|hydro]] energy and [[solar energy]].

SgurrEnergy was a supplier of technical advice to [[Airtricity]] on the [[Braes of Doune]] wind farm.<ref>[http://www.scottishrenewables.com/MultimediaGallery/1df99f66-e5bd-4823-82c3-10f3f501d30d.pdf Scottish Renewables Economics Impact Report 2007, Case Study 8] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701090050/http://www.scottishrenewables.com/MultimediaGallery/1df99f66-e5bd-4823-82c3-10f3f501d30d.pdf |date=1 July 2007 }}, ''Scottish Renewables.''</ref> This wind farm is a milestone as it makes the UK the 8th state in the world to meet the target of having at least 2GW of installed wind energy capacity.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/6344215.stm UK wind power reaches milestone], ''BBC news.''</ref> SgurrEnergy personnel have given presentations on industry related matters at several conferences and workshops.<ref>[http://www.bwea.com/pdf/trees/Sgurr.pdf The Effect of Forestry on Wind Regime and Energy Yield] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061110052751/http://www.bwea.com/pdf/trees/Sgurr.pdf |date=10 November 2006 }}, ''British Wind Energy Association.''</ref><ref>[http://www.all-energy.co.uk/Onshore_wind.html All Energy conference 2007] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928042407/http://www.all-energy.co.uk/Onshore_wind.html |date=28 September 2007 }}, ''All Energy.''</ref>

SgurrEnergy personnel provided ongoing technical support to [[ScottishPower]] on the development of [[Europe]]’s largest onshore wind farm, [[Whitelee]]. Located 20 miles south of [[Glasgow]] the wind farm became operational in 2009.  SgurrEnergy provided technical [[due diligence]] on the wind resource at Q7 offshore [[wind park]] off the coast of [[The Netherlands]].  This project is the world’s first bank financed [[wind park]].<ref>[http://www.dexia.com/e/news/press-release-desc.php?id=3370&p=0 Dexia (European bank) press release] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070210150437/http://www.dexia.com/e/news/press-release-desc.php?id=3370&p=0 |date=10 February 2007 }}, ''Dexia S.A.''</ref> In addition SgurrEnergy provided lenders Dexia and Rabobank with technical advice on the €153M Thorntonbank offshore wind farm off the Belgian coast.<ref>[http://www.energyengineering.co.uk/index.html Article (accessed June 2007)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928002840/http://www.energyengineering.co.uk/index.html |date=28 September 2007 }}, ''Energy Engineering''</ref> They are also providing technical advice on the construction of the first [[Finance|Western-financed]] [[wind farm]] to be built in [[China]].<ref>[http://www.sundayherald.com/business/businessnews/display.var.1510713.0.scots_put_wind_in_sails_of_chinese_turbine_project.php Scots put wind in the sails of Chinese turbine project] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927182742/http://www.sundayherald.com/business/businessnews/display.var.1510713.0.scots_put_wind_in_sails_of_chinese_turbine_project.php |date=27 September 2007 }}, ''Sunday Herald''</ref>

