'''Sulfur tetrachloride''' is an [[inorganic compound]] with [[chemical formula]] SCl<sub>4</sub>. It has only been obtained as an unstable pale yellow solid.  The corresponding SF<sub>4</sub> is a stable, useful reagent.

==Preparation and structure==
It is obtained by treating [[sulfur dichloride]] with [[chlorine]] at 193 K:
{{NumBlk|:|<math chem>\begin{matrix}{}\\
\ce{{SCl2} + Cl2 ->[\text{193 K}] SCl4}\\{}
\end{matrix}</math>|{{EquationRef|1}}}}
It melts with simultaneous decomposition above −20&nbsp;°C.<ref name="brauer">Georg Brauer: ''Handbuch der Präparativen Anorganischen Chemie''. {{de icon}}</ref>

Its solid structure is uncertain. It is probably the salt SCl<sub>3</sub><sup>+</sup>Cl<sup>−</sup>, since related salts are known with [[noncoordinating anion]]s.<ref>{{Greenwood&Earnshaw2nd}}</ref><ref>Christian, Beverly H.; Collins, Michael J.; Gillespie, Ronald J.; Sawyer, Jeffery F. "Preparations, Raman spectra, and crystal structures of (SCl<sub>3</sub>)(SbCl<sub>6</sub>), (SeCl<sub>3</sub>)(SbCl<sub>6</sub>), (SBr<sub>1.2</sub>Cl<sub>1.8</sub>)(SbCl<sup>6</sup>), (TeCl<sub>3</sub>)(AlCl<sub>4</sub>) (triclinic modification), (TeCl<sub>3</sub>)(SbF<sub>6</sub>), (TeCl<sub>3</sub>)(AsF<sub>6</sub>), and (TeF<sub>3</sub>)<sub>2</sub>(SO<sub>4</sub>)"  Inorganic Chemistry 1986, volume 25, 777-88. {{DOI|10.1021/ic00226a012}}</ref>  In contrast to this tetrachloride, SF<sub>4</sub> is a neutral molecule.<ref name=Goettel>Goettel, J. T., Kostiuk, N. and Gerken, M. (2013), ''The Solid-State Structure of SF<sub>4</sub>: The Final Piece of the Puzzle'' . Angew. Chem. Int. Ed., 52: 8037–8040. {{doi|10.1002/anie.201302917}}</ref>

==Reactions==
It decomposes above −30&nbsp;°C (242 K) to [[sulfur dichloride]] and chlorine.
{{NumBlk|:|<math chem>\begin{matrix}{}\\
\ce{SCl4 ->[\text{-15 }^\circ \ce C] {SCl2} + Cl2}\\{}
\end{matrix}</math>|{{EquationRef|2}}}}

It hydrolyzes readily:
{{NumBlk|:|<chem>{SCl4} + H2O -> {SOCl2} + {2HCl}</chem>|{{EquationRef|3}}}}

Sulfur tetrachloride reacts with water, producing [[hydrogen chloride]] and [[sulfur dioxide]] through the [[hydrolysis]] process.  Thionyl chloride is an implied intermediate.<ref>Holleman-Wiberg, Lehrbuch der Anorganischen Chemie, 101. Auflage, de Gruyter Verlag 1995 {{ISBN|3-11-012641-9}} {{de icon}}</ref>
{{NumBlk|:|<chem>{SCl4} + 2H2O -> {SO2} + {4HCl}</chem>|{{EquationRef|4}}}}

* Oxidized by [[nitric acid]]:
{{NumBlk|:|<chem>{SCl4} + {2HNO3} + 2H2O -> {H2SO4} + 2NO2 (^) + {4HCl}</chem>|{{EquationRef|5}}}}

