{{Infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] --> | name = The Great Derangement | title_orig = | translator = | image = The Great Derangement.jpg | caption = | author = [[Amitav Ghosh]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = India | language = [[English language|English]] | series = | genre = [[Non-fiction]] | publisher = Penguin Books | pub_date = 2016 | english_pub_date = | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover|hardback]]) | pages = | isbn = 9789386057433 | preceded_by = [[Incendiary Circumstances]] | followed_by = }}
'''''The Great Derangement''''' is a non-fiction book addressing [[climate change]] by Indian writer [[Amitav Ghosh]] published in 2016.<ref>http://www.amitavghosh.com/index.html</ref>
The book is composed of three parts, Part I deals with the stories, Part II is History and Part III is titled Politics. <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blogs.lse.ac.uk/lsereviewofbooks/2017/07/20/book-review-the-great-derangement-climate-change-and-the-unthinkable-by-amitav-ghosh/|title=Book Review: The Great Derangement: Climate Change and the Unthinkable by Amitav Ghosh|date=2017-07-20|work=LSE Review of Books|access-date=2018-03-14|language=en-US}}</ref> It examines our collective inability to spot the elephant in the room, namely "to grasp the scale and violence of the climate change".<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/G/bo22265507.html|title=The Great Derangement}}</ref>
It is a call to writers, artists, politicians, economists, industrialists, scientists, and all people to awaken out of the derangement we are presently living with.- "that we need not be concerned with earth and our environment in our actions, pursuits and activities."
It highlights how complex the climate change scenario is and how it impacts people and nations. The book is a call to open our eyes; peer into the future. It shows how deranged we might be right now and how there is a greater need to project these into the collective imagination of people through literature, works of fiction, collective debates. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/oct/28/amitav-ghosh-where-is-the-fiction-about-climate-change-|title=Amitav Ghosh: where is the fiction about climate change?|last=Ghosh|first=Amitav|date=2016-10-28|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.worldliteraturetoday.org/2017/march/great-derangement-climate-change-and-unthinkable-amitav-ghosh|title=The Great Derangement: Climate Change and the Unthinkable by Amitav Ghosh|date=2017-02-14|work=World Literature Today|access-date=2018-03-14|language=en}}</ref>
In the end Ghosh gives a deconstruction of the [[Paris Agreement|Paris agreement]] and ''[[Laudato si']]'' and call for collective action. ==Reviews==
* Raghu Karnad, '[https://thewire.in/50791/why-we-do-not-hear-the-waters-amitav-ghoshs-great-derangement/ Why We Do Not Hear the Waters: Amitav Ghosh’s ''Great Derangement'']', ''The Wire'' (12 July 2016)
